    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Illustration of the Dish logo with a white and red background." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/V3S1wHsMyXbgHa7_sVa8f1fwxqI=/0x0:3000x2000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73621168/acastro_STK052_01.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;If successful, the merger would create a combined satellite streaming business with around 20 million US subscribers.&lt;/em&gt; | Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="agrEIT"&gt;DirecTV has &lt;a href="https://www.anrdoezrs.net/links/8532386/type/dlg/sid/verge/https://www.directv.com/insider/directv-and-dish/" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;reached an agreement to acquire Dish&lt;/a&gt;, alongside its parent company EchoStar’s wider satellite TV business, for a single dollar — and assume $9.75 billion of Dish’s debt. Private equity firm TPG has arranged a two-step agreement to buy the remaining 70 percent of DirecTV that it didn’t already own from AT&amp;amp;T for a reported $7.6 billion and merge all of that with Dish.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="HbfnXc"&gt;The deal announced Monday would combine Dish’s roughly 8.1 million subscribers with the 11 million US subscribers under DirecTV, &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/09/30/business/dealbook/directv-dish-merger-deal.html?partner=slack&amp;amp;smid=sl-share"&gt;&lt;em&gt;The New York Times&lt;/em&gt; reports&lt;/a&gt;. The agreement would see AT&amp;amp;T exit as a part-owner of DirecTV, while EchoStar separates from its TV business to pursue the wonders of Open RAN 5G once the deal is closed in 2025.&lt;/p&gt;
