    <title>California governor vetoes major AI safety bill</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Photo illustration of a brain on a circuit board in red." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/yhYxdMmDLBE1DfYbCsGiJrAkdYQ=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73620125/STK414_AI_CHATBOT_H.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Illustration by Cath Virginia / The Verge | Photos from Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="MGZI28"&gt;California Governor Gavin Newsom vetoed the Safe and Secure Innovation for Frontier Artificial Intelligence Models Act &lt;a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=202320240SB1047"&gt;(SB 1047&lt;/a&gt;) today. In his &lt;a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/25178071-sb-1047-veto-message?responsive=1&amp;amp;title=1"&gt;veto message&lt;/a&gt;, Governor Newsom cited multiple factors in his decision, including the burden the bill would have placed on AI companies, California’s lead in the space, and a critique that the bill may be too broad.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p id="tsMFKU"&gt;“While well-intentioned, SB 1047 does not take into account whether an AI system is deployed in high-risk environments, involves critical decision-making or the use of sensitive data. Instead, the bill applies stringent standards to even the most basic functions — so long as a large system deploys it. I do not believe this is the best approach to protecting the public from real threats...&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/29/24232172/california-ai-safety-bill-1047-vetoed-gavin-newsom"&gt;Continue reading&amp;hellip;&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;/p&gt;

</content>
